T1  - Diversity, Diversification, and Profitability Among British Manufacturing Companies, 1972–1984
AU  - Grant, Robert M.
AU  - Jammine, Azar P.
AU  - Thomas, Howard
Y1  - 1988/12/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256338
DO  - 10.5465/256338
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 771
EP  - 801
VL  - 31
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study investigated the causal relationships between diversity, diversification, and profitability among 304 large British manufacturing companies that differed in both product and multinational diversity. Diversity and profitability were positively related up to a point; after that point, increases in product diversity were associated with declining profitability. The results were unclear with respect to the underlying causal relationships. Product diversification did not increase profitability, and there was limited evidence that profitability promoted diversification. For multinational diversification, however, we found that profitability in the home market encouraged overseas expansion that in turn increased profitability.
AB  - This study investigated the causal relationships between diversity, diversification, and profitability among 304 large British manufacturing companies that differed in both product and multinational diversity. Diversity and profitability were positively related up to a point; after that point, increases in product diversity were associated with declining profitability. The results were unclear with respect to the underlying causal relationships. Product diversification did not increase profitability, and there was limited evidence that profitability promoted diversification. For multinational diversification, however, we found that profitability in the home market encouraged overseas expansion that in turn increased profitability.
