TY  - JOUR
T1  - Leaders, Riverboat Gamblers, or Purposeful Unintended Consequences in the Management of Complex, Dangerous Technologies
AU  - Osborn, Richard N.
AU  - Jackson, Daniel H.
Y1  - 1988/12/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256345
DO  - 10.5465/256345
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 924
EP  - 947
VL  - 31
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Utilities' investment in nuclear-generating technology and prior earnings growth were used to predict variations in three measures of plant-operating safety. The pattern of results is consistent with three interpretations: (1) some historically successful utilities that are heavily committed to nuclear power provide leadership; (2) such utilities are gambling with public safety: and (3) a general pattern of purposeful unintended consequences arising from ignorance and self-serving myths combined with the risk propensities of executives and leading to hitherto unidentified threats to public safety.
AB  - Utilities' investment in nuclear-generating technology and prior earnings growth were used to predict variations in three measures of plant-operating safety. The pattern of results is consistent with three interpretations: (1) some historically successful utilities that are heavily committed to nuclear power provide leadership; (2) such utilities are gambling with public safety: and (3) a general pattern of purposeful unintended consequences arising from ignorance and self-serving myths combined with the risk propensities of executives and leading to hitherto unidentified threats to public safety.
