T1  - A Contingency Approach to Strategy Implementation at the Business-Unit Level: Integrating Administrative Mechanisms with Strategy
AU  - Govindarajan, Vijay
Y1  - 1988/12/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256341
DO  - 10.5465/256341
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 828
EP  - 853
VL  - 31
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study focused on what is perhaps the most critical aspect of strategy implementation in large, multibusiness organizations: recognizing that different business units within the same corporation often pursue different strategies and that the administrative mechanisms that corporate headquarters use to manage those businesses should differ. This study compared the results of bivariate and systems approaches to fit. Implications of the results for theory development and managerial practice are discussed.
AB  - This study focused on what is perhaps the most critical aspect of strategy implementation in large, multibusiness organizations: recognizing that different business units within the same corporation often pursue different strategies and that the administrative mechanisms that corporate headquarters use to manage those businesses should differ. This study compared the results of bivariate and systems approaches to fit. Implications of the results for theory development and managerial practice are discussed.
